The Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela has called on the International Criminal Court (ICC) to investigate allegations of crimes against her by the United States of America as a result of imposition of economic blockades and unilateral coercive measures referred to as sanctions. Venezuela’s  ambassador to Nigeria,David Velasquez, said that his country has suffered untold hardship inflicted on it by the imposition of unwarranted sanctions and undue interference in the affairs of his country by the United States (US). According to him, even though the US is not a signatory to the Rome Statute, his country has invoked Article 7 of the Rome Statute to request the ICC to launch investigations against US for crimes against humanity. The lawsuit according to the envoy, presented to the ICC indicates that the unilateral coercive measures imposed on the people and government of Venezuela by the United States government since 2014 constituted a crime against humanity. In the document presented to the ICC, Venezuela recalled documented cases and facts against the US which has impacted negatively on the Venezuelan population especially infants, adults, food supply, public services,education, transport and healthcare. According to him, child mortality and undernourishment rates have increased in  Venezuela due to ‘ the blockade on food and medicine purchases imposed by the United states.’ Ambassador Velasquez believes the ICC has a moral and legal authority to look into the suit by his government against the US in the interest of Justice, equity and good conscience.